- cocos2d-x version: 3.11
- devices test on: iPad Air 2
- developing environments
  - NDK version: N/A
  - Xcode version: 7.2.1
  - VS version: N/A
  - brower type and version:

We have discovered several large and concerning memory leaks originating from spidermonkey in our Cocos2d-x project on the iOS platform. We have not confirmed if this issue is or isn't happening on other platforms due to lack of good memory leak tooling on our other development platform (Android). Our rough polling of Heap Size in my Android application seems to suggest that this issue is also happening on Android, but we don't have solid proof of this. The two principle leaks seem to originate from the following two actions:
- Calling eval (either directly or indirectly) on any script code will leak the string of the evaluated code.
- Calling a function that has undergone cc.Class's _super variable replacement will cause the "ArgumentsData" object of Spidermonkeys Internal "ArgumentsObject" to leak. ArgumentsObject here is spidermonkeys internal C++ representation of the "arguments" object in a Javascript function. 

We believe this is related to issue https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-x/issues/16291, and that issue is caused by these leaks. 

Examining either of these action's in Apple's Instruments program produces the following data:

