For the eval() case
Steps to Reproduce:
1. Examine a Cocos2d-x application with the Instruments program, examining memory leaks.
2. Repeated eval a string of arbitrary Javascript.
3. Watch as leaked memory rises.

For the _super case
Steps to Reproduce:
1. Examine a Cocos2d-x application with the Instruments program, examining memory leaks.
2. Run the following code:

```
var HelloWorld = cc.Layer.extend({
                    ctor:function () {
                        this._super();
                        this.scheduleUpdate();
                    },
                    update: function () {
                        var node = new cc.Node();
                        this.addChild(node);
                        this.scheduleOnce(function () {
                            node.removeFromParent();
                        });
                    }
                });

```
1. Watch as leaked memory rises.
2. Now, if you were to create an update function that does not undergo super replacement, this leak will not occur.

cocos2d-x version: 3.11

Steps to Reproduce:

``` c++
class *a = A::create();
scheduler->scheduleUpdate(a, 0, false);
scheduler->unscheduleUpdate(a);
a->release();
a = nullptr;

class *b = B::create();
when the address of b is same to a
scheduler->scheduleUpdate(b, 0, false);
```

schedulerUpdate will set markedForDeletion to false, but not update callback

all the code is in one update frame
